net.sf.kdgcommons.test

Class SelfMock<MockedType>

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.sf.kdgcommons.test.SelfMock<MockedType>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    InvocationHandler

    public abstract class SelfMock<MockedType>
extends Object
implements InvocationHandler
    A reflection-based proxy that invokes requests on itself. This class is intended to be subclassed, with the subclass implementing the methods that are to be mocked.

    To use, construct with the interface to be mocked (only one allowed, due to Java parameterization), then call getInstance() to create the proxy instance. 

         SelfMock<Map<String,String>> mock = new SelfMock(Map.class)
     {
         public Object get(Object key)
         {
             return "something";
         }
     };

     Map<String,String> mocked = mock.getInstance();

    All invocations are counted and the invocation arguments retained. You can retrieve the count and arguments, and perform assertions on them: 

          String value = mocked.get("anything");

      assertEquals(1, mock.getInvocationCount("get"));
      assertEquals("anything", mock.getInvocationArg("get", 0, 0, String.class));

    Calls to an unmocked method throw UnsupportedOperationException.

      • getInstance

        public MockedType getInstance()
        Returns a proxy instance that passes invocations to this mock. Multiple calls will return different proxy instances.

      • getInvocationCount

        public int getInvocationCount(String methodName)
        Returns the number of times the named function was invoked. This does not differentiate between overloaded methods: all methods with the same name is counted together.

      • getInvocationArgs

        public Object[] getInvocationArgs(String methodName,
                                  int invocationIndex)
        Returns the arguments passed to a particular invocation of the named method (using zero-based counting). This is primarily useful when dealing with overloaded methods, where you might not know what types the arguments are. If you know the arguments, getInvocationArg(java.lang.String, int, int, java.lang.Class<T>) is a better choice.

        Note: this method returns the actual argument array that was passed to the invocation handler. Don't modify it unless you want to invalidate your tests.

        Throws:
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - if accessing a call that was never made.

      • getInvocationArg

                              int argumentIndex,
                              Class<T> argType)
        Returns a specific invocation argument, cast to a particular type. Both indexes are zero-based.

      • getMostRecentInvocationArgs

        public Object[] getMostRecentInvocationArgs(String methodName)

If you know the arguments, getMostRecentInvocationArg(java.lang.String, int, java.lang.Class<T>) is a better choice.

        Note: this method returns the actual argument array that was passed to the invocation handler. Don't modify it unless you want to invalidate your tests.
